00:25:47.999 --> 00:25:53.200
technology start up or technology company
whether that be Groupon or Google.

00:25:53.200 --> 00:25:59.159
How do you plan to ensure that Chicago continues
to remain competitive as a global business

00:25:59.159 --> 00:26:05.710
hub and is able to attract and retain the
best sort of talent here to build the city

00:26:05.710 --> 00:26:07.571
and to build the work force around the city?

00:26:07.571 --> 00:26:11.779
&gt;&gt;Miguel del Valle: First of all, I think
we will continue to be very competitive. We

00:26:11.779 --> 00:26:18.410
have some of the best universities in the
country right here -- University of Chicago,

00:26:18.410 --> 00:26:25.240
Northwestern. We have a great public university,
University of Illinois. And so we're gonna

00:26:25.240 --> 00:26:27.789
remain very competitive.

00:26:27.789 --> 00:26:34.380
The question is how do we create more opportunities
for more people in the City of Chicago so

00:26:34.380 --> 00:26:41.190
that we're not a Tale of Two Cities, extreme
poverty in the surrounding areas. And I say

00:26:41.190 --> 00:26:48.360
that [chuckles] when I take 290 coming in
sometimes and I see that beautiful skyline

00:26:48.360 --> 00:26:54.730
in front me, to the east of me I see the Emerald
City. I always think of the Wizard of Oz ?

00:26:54.730 --> 00:26:55.730
&gt;&gt;David Lieber: [chuckles]

00:26:55.730 --> 00:26:58.269
&gt;&gt;Miguel del Valle: and what it took to get
to the Emerald City. Sometimes I feel that

00:26:58.269 --> 00:27:04.470
that's what a lot of people do. How do you
get to that and how do you expand those borders

00:27:04.470 --> 00:27:10.110
so that everyone is part of that Emerald City?

00:27:10.110 --> 00:27:16.039
And I think that certainly dealing with the
quality of public education is an important

00:27:16.039 --> 00:27:23.749
piece of that. I've talked to small manufacturers
who want to develop advanced manufacturing

00:27:23.749 --> 00:27:29.379
here in parts of the city on the west side,
and the first thing they tell me is that they're

00:27:29.379 --> 00:27:32.499
concerned about being able to find the skilled
work force.

00:27:32.499 --> 00:27:38.059
And so that's why programs like the one, the
Austin Polytech Program on the west side where

00:27:38.059 --> 00:27:42.980
they're working with a couple of manufacturers
and training the kids, machinists to deal

00:27:42.980 --> 00:27:47.179
with today's equipment. More of that needs
to be done.

00:27:47.179 --> 00:27:54.840
On the tax policy side, folks, I know it's
painful. I've yet to talk to a business person

00:27:54.840 --> 00:28:00.600
who says, "Yeah, go ahead increase my taxes."
I don't know of anyone who does that, who

00:28:00.600 --> 00:28:03.360
says that. I'm sure they're out there.

00:28:03.360 --> 00:28:13.989
But the fact of the matter is that Illinois
was about to start defaulting. Providers have

00:28:13.989 --> 00:28:22.269
waited nine months, eight months to be paid.
The only state worse than us was California,

00:28:22.269 --> 00:28:30.179
in the country. There was really no other
alternative but to raise that tax. I'm glad

00:28:30.179 --> 00:28:36.490
it was done temporarily and not permanent
even though it's the legislature so they could

00:28:36.490 --> 00:28:41.369
always go back in three or four years and
then make the tax increase permanent. I would

00:28:41.369 --> 00:28:48.779
hope that that doesn't happen. But the fact
of the matter is that we need to pay our bills

00:28:48.779 --> 00:28:54.980
and I really think that this threat that's
out there, the Governor of Indiana and New

00:28:54.980 --> 00:28:58.120
Jersey putting up a welcome sign --

00:28:58.120 --> 00:28:59.120
&gt;&gt;David Lieber: Right.

00:28:59.120 --> 00:29:05.360
&gt;&gt;Miguel del Valle: and trying to lure companies
away from Illinois is just not something that

00:29:05.360 --> 00:29:13.379
I think is gonna play out. Sure, some people
will make a decision based on that obligation.

00:29:13.379 --> 00:29:23.289
But I think Chicago is strong and I think
many parts of the state are strong and businesses

00:29:23.289 --> 00:29:24.289
will do well here.

00:29:24.289 --> 00:29:30.690
&gt;&gt;David Lieber: Let's talk about something
that's maybe not nearly as sexy, tax increment

00:29:30.690 --> 00:29:34.690
financing. You've talked a little bit on the
campaign trail about TIF surpluses which I

00:29:34.690 --> 00:29:39.220
think surprised a lot of Chicagoans to hear
the term "surplus" and "Chicago" in the same

00:29:39.220 --> 00:29:44.440
sentence. But can you talk a little bit more
about the TIF surplus and what if anything

00:29:44.440 --> 00:29:47.360
you might do with any TIF surplus funds?

00:29:47.360 --> 00:29:52.070
&gt;&gt;Miguel del Valle: Well first of all we don't
know what the amount is and we're the ones,

00:29:52.070 --> 00:29:59.110
we being the city, will determine what the
surplus is. But that determination gets made

00:29:59.110 --> 00:30:05.409
by looking at what's obligated and what projects
are in the pipeline and once you subtract

00:30:05.409 --> 00:30:09.851
all of that, then you see what's there, 'cause
TIF's generate about $500 million a year.

00:30:09.851 --> 00:30:20.100
And this year for this current fiscal year
we used about $30 million or so for the budget

00:30:20.100 --> 00:30:25.759
to deal with this year's budget. That triggered
the release of dollars because it's a formula

00:30:25.759 --> 00:30:34.659
driven process to CPS of about $90 million.
I anticipate that we're going to have to do

00:30:34.659 --> 00:30:42.549
the same thing for fiscal year 2012, because
we are at this point talking about a $650

00:30:42.549 --> 00:30:48.239
million deficit and my guess is that it's
going to be higher than that. And so we're

00:30:48.239 --> 00:30:49.970
going to have to use those dollars.

00:30:49.970 --> 00:30:59.220
Now I also believe that TIF's should be created
for what was originally intended and that

00:30:59.220 --> 00:31:05.600
is to spur economic activity in blighted areas.
We haven't done that. A lot of TIF dollars

00:31:05.600 --> 00:31:13.350
have gone into the downtown area and so the
Mercantile Exchange got something like $15

00:31:13.350 --> 00:31:18.539
million and Boeing and others have gotten
money.

00:31:18.539 --> 00:31:26.059
I wanna see TIF's used to stimulate economic
activity in areas that need it number one,

00:31:26.059 --> 00:31:31.989
and I want to see it tied to job creation.
And so if the job creation doesn't take place

00:31:31.989 --> 00:31:38.549
then those TIF dollars oughta come back to
the city. So we're gonna do a lot of work

00:31:38.549 --> 00:31:48.289
with TIF's. But I believe that tax increment
financing is a good economic development tool.

00:31:48.289 --> 00:31:50.890
I'm not one of those who wants to do away
with TIF's.

